text: Fork package clone onto computer. haven’t done , recommend using usethis::create_from_github("YihaoTancn/pvEBayes", fork = TRUE). Install development dependencies devtools::install_dev_deps(), make sure package passes R CMD check running devtools::check(). R CMD check doesn’t pass cleanly, ’s good idea ask help continuing. Create Git branch pull request (PR). recommend using usethis::pr_init("brief-description--change"). Make changes, commit git, create PR running usethis::pr_push(), following prompts browser. title PR briefly describe change. body PR contain Fixes #issue-number. user-facing changes, add bullet top NEWS.md (.e. just first header). title: Analyzing SRS frequency table with pvEBayes
text: Contemporary drug postmarketing surveillance largely relies collection spontaneous reports suspected adverse drug events pharmaceutical companies, healthcare professionals, patients. reports curated stored spontaneous reporting systems (SRS), usually organized large frequency table downstream data analysis. consider SRS dataset cataloging AE reports II AE rows across JJ drug columns. Let NijN_{ij} denote number reported cases ii-th AE jj-th drug, =1,...,Ii = 1,..., j=1,...,Jj = 1,..., J. Therefore, AE-drug pairwise occurrences AE-reports summarized ×JI \times J contingency table, (,j)(,j)-th cell catalogs observed count NijN_{ij} indicating number cases involving ii-th AE jj-th drug. Methods implemented package assumes observed count NijN_{ij} conditional EijE_{ij} Nij∣Eij∼Poisson(Eijλij),\begin{equation} \label{eqn:model-poisson-likelihood} N_{ij} \mid E_{ij} \sim \operatorname{Poisson}(E_{ij}\lambda_{ij}),   \end{equation} parameter λij≥0\lambda_{ij} \geq 0 relative reporting ratio, signal strength, (,j)(, j)-th pair measuring ratio actual expected count arising due dependence null baseline expected count. Therefore, {λij}\{\lambda_{ij}\} key parameters interest. large λij\lambda_{ij} indicates strong association drug AE. Let gg prior density function signal strength parameters AE-drug pairs: λij∼g\lambda_{ij} \sim g. , context Poisson model, marginal probability mass function NijN_{ij} given : p(Nij)=∫0∞g(λij)fpois(Nij∣λijEij)dλij, p(N_{ij}) = \int_0^{\infty} g(\lambda_{ij}) \ f_{\text{pois}}(N_{ij} \mid \lambda_{ij}E_{ij}) \ d\lambda_{ij},  fpois(N∣λ)f_{\text{pois}}(N \mid \lambda) probability mass function Poisson random variable mean λ\lambda evaluated NN. empirical Bayes framework, prior distribution consequently estimated data maximizing log marginal likelihood: ĝ=argmaxg∑=1I∑j=1Jlogp(Nij). \hat g = \mathop{\arg \max}\limits_{g} \sum_{=1}^\sum_{j=1}^J \log p(N_{ij}).  , estimated posterior density λ\lambda given NijN_{ij} : p̂(λ∣Nij)=ĝ(λ)fpois(Nij∣λEij)p̂(Nij), \hat{\text{p}}(\lambda \mid N_{ij}) = \frac{\hat g(\lambda) f_{\text{pois}}(N_{ij} \mid \lambda E_{ij})}{\hat{\text{p}}(N_{ij})},  p̂(Nij)=∫0∞ĝ(λij)fpois(Nij∣λijEij)dλij\hat{\text{p}}(N_{ij}) = \int_0^{\infty} \hat g(\lambda_{ij})f_{\text{pois}}(N_{ij}\mid \lambda_{ij}E_{ij}) \ d\lambda_{ij}. empirical Bayes models implemented ‘pvEBayes’ share structure described ; differ assumptions prior distribution. Gamma-Poisson Shrinker (GPS) adopts two-component gamma mixture prior. K-gamma model generalizes GPS allowing K-component gamma mixture, K user-specified. Koenker-Mizera (KM) Efron models use nonparametric discrete mixture prior, point masses pre-specified grid. general-gamma model employs nonparametric sparse gamma mixture distribution. Package ‘pvEBayes’ provides implementations empirical Bayes methods pharmacovigilance mentioned . provides tools effectively fitting models spontaneous reporting system (SRS) frequency tables, extracting summaries, performing hyperparameter tuning, generating graphical summaries (eye plots heatmaps) signal detection estimation. following provide example (borrowed Tan et al.) SRS data analyzing ‘pvEBayes’.

title: Analyzing SRS frequency table with pvEBayes
text: interest lies finding important adverse events estimating corresponding signal strength 6 statin drugs. achieved fitting empirical Bayes models pvEBayes() SRS data. begin fitting general-gamma model dataset. models mentioned used modifying ‘model’ argument. illustration, fit model fixed hyperparameter value $ = 0.5$ using pvEBayes() function. return argument specifies component summary function return. Valid options include: “prior parameters”, “likelihood”, “detected signal”, “posterior draws”. set NULL (default), components returned list. example, show detected signals. package, suggest tuning general-gamma model AIC BIC, can accessed ‘AIC()’ ‘BIC()’ functions, shown : practice, one can specify list candidate α\alpha values, fit general-gamma model , compute corresponding AIC BIC, select model lowest AIC BIC. Instead manually , one can use ‘pvEBayes_tune()’ function, implements steps. relevant code given :
code: gg_given_alpha <-  pvEBayes(statin2025_44,  model = "general-gamma",  alpha = 0.5  )   gg_given_alpha_detected_signal <- summary(gg_given_alpha,  return = "detected signal"  )  sum(gg_given_alpha_detected_signal) #> [1] 105 AIC(gg_given_alpha) #> [1] 3802.753  BIC(gg_given_alpha) #> [1] 4016.649 gg_tune_statin44 <- pvEBayes_tune(statin2025_44,  model = "general-gamma",  alpha_vec = c(0, 0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.7, 0.9),  use_AIC = TRUE  ) #> The alpha value selected under AIC is 0.3, #> The alpha value selected under BIC is 0.1. #>   alpha      AIC      BIC num_mixture #> 1   0.0 4551.612 4697.962          13 #> 2   0.1 3799.011 3990.392          17 #> 3   0.3 3798.874 4001.513          18 #> 4   0.5 3802.753 4016.649          19 #> 5   0.7 3822.367 4081.295          23 #> 6   0.9 3906.526 4323.061          37

AE-drug combination, number reports (N), estimated null value (E), estimated posterior probability signal given. deeper blue color indicates stronger evidence signal.  eyeplot visualizes empirical posterior inferences 10 prominent AEs across 6 statin drugs computed empirical Bayesian posterior distributions signal strengths {λij}\{\lambda_{ij}\} obtained general-gamma model fitted statin2025_44 dataset. points bars represent posterior medians 90% equi-tailed credible intervals corresponding AE-drug pair specific {λij}\{\lambda_{ij}\}, different colors indicating results different statin drugs. red dotted vertical line represents value ‘1’. texts right provide number observations well null baseline expected counts independence AE-drug pair.

text: pvEBayes R package implements suite nonparametric empirical Bayes methods pharmacovigilance, including Gamma-Poisson Shrinker (GPS), K-gamma, general-gamma, Koenker-Mizera (KM), Efron models. provides tools fitting models spontaneous reporting system (SRS) frequency tables, extracting summaries, performing hyperparameter tuning, generating graphical summaries (eye plots heatmaps) signal detection estimation. Spontaneous Reporting System (SRS) Table: drug safety SRS dataset catalogs AE reports AE rows across J drug columns. Let Nij{N_{ij}} denote number reported cases -th AE j-th drug, =1,...,{= 1,..., } j=1,...,J{j = 1,..., J}. Empirical Bayes modeling disproportionality analysis: assume AE-drug pair, Nij∼Poisson(λijEij)N_{ij} \sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda_{ij} E_{ij}), Eij{E_{ij}} expected baseline value, measuring expected count AE-drug pair association betweeni-th AE j-th drug. parameter λij≥0{\lambda_{ij} \geq 0} represents relative reporting ratio, signal strength, (,j){(, j)}-th pair, measuring ratio actual expected count arising due dependence null baseline expected count. Med., 2025) broaden role disproportionality signal estimation. use flexible non-parametric empirical Bayes models enables nuanced empirical Bayes posterior inference (parameter estimation uncertainty quantification) signal strength parameter {λij}\{ \lambda_{ij} \}. allows researchers distinguish AE-drug pairs appear similar binary signal detection framework. example, AE-drug pairs signal strengths 1.5 4.0 significantly greater 1 detected signal. differences signal strength may distinct implications medical clinical contexts. methods included pvEBayes differ assumptions prior distribution. Implemented methods include Gamma-Poisson Shrinker (GPS), Koenker-Mizera (KM) method, Efron’s nonparametric empirical Bayes approach, K-gamma model, general-gamma model. selection prior distribution critical Bayesian analysis. GPS model uses gamma mixture prior assuming signal/non-signal structure SRS data. However, real-world setting, signal strengths (λij){(\lambda_{ij})} often heterogeneous thus follows multi-modal distribution, making difficult assume parametric prior. Non-parametric empirical Bayes models (KM, Efron, K-gamma general-gamma) address challenge utilizing flexible prior general mixture form estimating prior distribution data-driven way. Implementations: KM method existing implementation REBayes package, relies Mosek, commercial convex optimization solver, may limit accessibility due licensing issues. pvEBayes package provides alternative fully open-source implementation KM method using CVXR. Efron’s method also general nonparametric empirical Bayes implementation deconvolveR package; however, implementation support exposure offset parameter Poisson model, corresponds expected null value Eij{E_{ij}}. pvEBayes, implementation Efron’s method adapted modified deconvolveR support Eij{E_{ij}} Poisson model. addition, package implements novel bi-level Expectation Conditional Maximization (ECM) algorithm proposed Tan et al. (2025) efficient parameter estimation gamma mixture prior based models mentioned .

title: Fit a general-gamma, GPS, K-gamma, KM or efron model for a contingency table. — pvEBayes
text: function implements ECM algorithm proposed Tan et al. (2025), providing stable efficient implementation Gamma-Poisson Shrinker(GPS), K-gamma "general-gamma" methods signal estimation signal detection Spontaneous Reporting System (SRS) data table. Method "GPS" proposed DuMouchel (1999) parametric empirical Bayes model two gamma mixture prior distribution. Methods "K-gamma" "general-gamma" non-parametric empirical Bayes models, introduced Tan et al. (2025). number mixture components "K" needs prespecified fitting "K-gamma" model. "general-gamma", mixture weights regularized Dirichlet hyper prior hyperparameter \(0 \leq \alpha < 1\) controls shrinkage strength. "alpha" approaches 0, less non-empty mixture components exist fitted model. \(\alpha = 0\), Dirichlet distribution improper prior still offering reasonable posterior inference represents strongest shrinkage "general-gamma" model. Parameter estimation "KM" model formulated convex optimization problem. objective function constraints follow construction REBayes. Parameter estimation performed using open-source convex optimization package CVXR. implementation "efron" model package adapted deconvolveR package, developed Bradley Efron Balasubramanian Narasimhan. original implementation deconvolveR support exposure offset parameter Poisson model, corresponds expected null value (\(E_{ij}\)) AE-drug combination. address , modified relevant code allow inclusion \(E_{ij}\) Poisson likelihood. addition, implemented method estimating degrees freedom, enabling AIC- BIC-based hyperparameter selection "efron" model (Tan et al. 2025). See pvEBayes_tune details.

code: set.seed(1) ref_table <- statin2025_44  # set up signal matrix with one signal at entry (1,1) sig_mat <- matrix(1, nrow(ref_table), ncol(ref_table)) sig_mat[1, 1] <- 2  # set up structural zero matrix Z <- matrix(0, nrow(ref_table), ncol(ref_table)) Z[5, 1] <- 1  simu_table <- generate_contin_table(   ref_table = ref_table,   signal_mat = sig_mat,   n_table = 1,   Variation = TRUE,   zi_indic_mat = Z )[[1]][[1]]   # fit general-gamma model with a specified alpha fit <- pvEBayes(   contin_table = simu_table,   model = "general-gamma",   alpha = 0.3,   n_posterior_draws = 1000,   E = NULL,   maxi = NULL )  # fit K-gamma model with K = 3 fit_Kgamma <- pvEBayes(   contin_table = simu_table, model = "K-gamma",   K = 3, n_posterior_draws = 1000 )   # fit Efron model with specified hyperparameters # p = 40, c0 = 0.05  if (FALSE) { # \dontrun{ fit_efron <- pvEBayes(   contin_table = simu_table,   model = "efron",   p = 40,   c0 = 0.05,   n_posterior_draws = 1000 ) } # }

title: pvEBayes 0.2.0
text: Added new implementation Koenker-Mizera (KM) model using ‘CVXR’ package. Removed dependency ‘REBayes’. Removed suggested dependency ‘Rmosek’. Added support supplying prespecified expected‐null baseline estimator via E argument ‘pvEBayes()’. Added package vignette. Added CITATION file, enabling use citation(“pvEBayes”).
